_This issue is a **feature discussion**._

For now, the way to write a ObjectType is as below:

```Python
class Hero(ObjectType):
    name = Field(List(String), only_first_name=Boolean())
    age = Int()

    def resolve_name(self, info, only_first_name=False):
        if only_first_name:
            return [self._first_name]
        return [self._first_name, self._last_name]

    def resolve_age(self, info):
        return self._age
```

I define name twice (`Hero.name` and `Hero.resolve_name`) because we have to define types of arguments and return value. This will cause some reading and writing problems.

Since python3, annotation feature bring a native way to describe types. With annotation, we can rewrite this class with a clearer way:

```python
class Heroine(AnnotationObjectType):

    def name(self, info, only_first_name: Boolean() = False) -> List(String):
        if only_first_name:
            return [self._first_name]
        return [self._first_name, self._last_name]

    def age(self, info) -> Int():
        return self._age


print(Heroine.name.__annotations__)
# {'only_first_name': <graphene.types.scalars.Boolean object at 0x104cb8550>, 'return': <graphene.types.structures.List object at 0x105742f28>}
```

`AnnotationObjectType` shouldn't be difficult to write if we somehow transform `AnnotationObjectType` into `ObjectType`. But I think a looooot of cases should be tested before being released.

Of cause even if we write an `AnnotationObjectType` class, `ObjectType` class will not be dropped since python2.7 don't support annotation.

I would like to hear your guys' comments and suggestions before doing this.

